    "questions": [
        {
            "id": "ef1ab9e9a072456fafd42",
            "questionText": "A child is on a swing set performing simple harmonic motion. The swing has a length of $!$L = 2.5\\text{ m}$!$. If the maximum angular displacement of the swing is $!$\\theta_{max} = 0.2\\text{ radians}$!$, determine the maximum velocity, $!$v_{max}$!$, of the child during the swing's motion. Assume the acceleration due to gravity is $!$g = 9.8\\text{ m/s}^2$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "be83ee149ea243fa9dd7b",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct expression for the angular frequency $!$\\omega$!$ of a simple pendulum undergoing small oscillations. Choose the formula that correctly relates $!$\\omega$!$ with $!$g$!$ and $!$L$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "eed7f907-b397-4f8c-8f17-d4f199db79ab"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega = \\sqrt{\\frac{g}{L}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega = \\sqrt{\\frac{L}{g}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega = 2\\pi\\sqrt{\\frac{g}{L}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "f74e0f5233464dbd97935",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have the relation, use the provided values $!$g = 9.8\\text{ m/s}^2$!$ and $!$L = 2.5\\text{ m}$!$ to calculate the angular frequency $!$\\omega$!$. What is the computed value?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.98"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "rad/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "eed7f907-b397-4f8c-8f17-d4f199db79ab"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "fe4629b690224428babd6",
                    "stepText": "Now, consider the relation for the maximum tangential velocity $!$v_{max}$!$ in terms of the angular frequency $!$\\omega$!$, the length $!$L$!$, and the maximum angular displacement $!$\\theta_{max}$!$. Choose the correct expression from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "bfe73a51-56e1-42c2-b400-35e2aa8f4737"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v_{max} = L \\omega \\theta_{max}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v_{max} = \\frac{L \\theta_{max}}{\\omega}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v_{max} = \\frac{\\omega}{L \\theta_{max}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "ed4d9044e09a448e81cf5",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the expression you selected, calculate the maximum velocity $!$v_{max}$!$ by multiplying the length of the swing, the angular frequency, and the maximum angular displacement. Use $!$L = 2.5\\text{ m}$!$, $!$\\theta_{max} = 0.2\\text{ radians}$!$, and your computed $!$\\omega \\approx 1.98\\text{ rad/s}$!$. What is the maximum velocity?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.99"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "bfe73a51-56e1-42c2-b400-35e2aa8f4737"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "7cb59c7021ca4f94bc503",
            "questionText": "A car's suspension system, modeled as a spring-mass system, oscillates after hitting a bump. The car has a mass of $!$m = 1500 \\text{ kg}$!$, and the suspension spring has a spring constant of $!$k = 60000 \\text{ N/m}$!$. After hitting a bump, the system initially has a total energy of $!$E_T = 300 \\text{ J}$!$. Calculate the maximum velocity, $!$v_{max}$!$, of the car's oscillation after hitting the bump.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "f8ceb65d3b3a4a9680922",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the energy scenario. At maximum velocity, all the total energy is kinetic. Which of the following formulas correctly expresses kinetic energy in terms of mass and velocity?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e6cbee8e-24f0-49b0-acff-dee433badd26"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\frac{1}{2} m v^2 = E_T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$m v = E_T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\frac{1}{2} m v = E_T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "ee8d821c6bf24272aa85d",
                    "stepText": "Great, with the correct kinetic energy formula in place, let's substitute the known values to solve for $!$v_{max}^2$!$. Using the relation $!$v_{max}^2 = \\frac{2E_T}{m}$!$, calculate its numerical value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.4"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m^2/s^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "8cc0ceb710da48b7ae14f",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have $!$v_{max}^2$!$, let's determine $!$v_{max}$!$ by taking its square root. Compute the square root of the previous result.",
